<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>

<chapter xml:id="ch_integration" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Integration in Several Variables</title>
<introduction>
    <p>There are many aspects of integration in several variables. In this chapter we  first discuss 
    the definition and evaluation of the integral of 
	well behaved <em>scalar functions</em>  on simple domains 
	in the Euclidean space <m>\bbR^{n}</m> which are generalizations of rectangular boxes, triangles
	and tetrahedrons in
	two and three dimensions, called <em>hypercubes</em> and <em>simplexes</em>
	respectively. We then extend the discussion
	to <em>domains with piecewise <m>C^{1}</m> boundary</em>.
	In the next chapter we will extend the discussion, where the domain of
	integration is a lower dimensional surface in the Euclidean space <m>\bbR^{n}</m>, 
	and the integrand is given in terms of <em>coupling</em> of a vector field and the tangent
	plane of the surface, or more formally, the integration of a differential form over a surface or
	a <term>singular chain</term>.  </p>
	
	<p>Below are some main issues to be addressed.</p>
	
	<ol>
  <li>It is not too different from integration in one dimension if one only discusses integrals of a scalar function
  defined in a multi-dimensional rectangle. One can establish a similar integrability criterion
  and prove a version of the <term>Fubini Theorem</term>, 
  which reduces the evaluation of the integral to iterated one variable integrals.</li>
  <li><p>Complications come in when one tries to define integrals in more general domains in
  multi-dimensions. One main issue is how to properly define <term>partitions</term>. 
  Partitions in the Riemann
  sense require that there is a well defined notion of area (volume) for the <em>cells</em> used in the 
  partition, which is why traditionally we only confine to rectangular cells in partitions. Another aspect
  is that we want the cells to be <em>non-overlapping</em>, and this is relatively easy to achieve using
  rectangular cells. </p>
  <p>One way to resolve the issue of decomposing a general domain as a
  non-overlapping union of rectangular cells is to enclose the domain (required to be bounded) by
  a rectangular box and extend the integrand to be <m>0</m> in the complement. This would 
  require accounting for the contributions to the upper and lower integrals
  from  those rectangular cells in the partition of the enclosing rectangular box that "<em>straddle</em>" between
  the domain and its complement. This is not too difficult to address, but one does need
  to control the <em>measure</em> of the boundary of the domain of integration.</p></li>
  <li><p>In any integration theory one expects the integral <m>\int_{A}f</m> to be linear in the integrand
  <m>f</m>, namely, for any integrable <m>f, g</m>, and constants <m>a, b</m>,
  <me>
  \int_{A} \left( a f+ b g\right)\, = a \int_{A}f  + b \int_{A}g.
  </me>
  It is also natural to expect that when <m>A</m> can be decomposed as 
  a non-overlapping union of two subsets <m>A_{1}\cup A_{2}</m>,
  <me>\int_{A}f =\int_{A_{1}}f + \int_{A_{2}}f</me>.
  One also hopes that the converse holds: if the terms on the right hand side are well defined, then the left
  hand side should be well defined and equals the right hand side.</p>
  <p>In one dimension this is certainly true when <m>A_{1}, A_{2}</m> are intervals. But
  even in that context, Riemann integration theory places restrictions on these sets:
  if we take <m>A=[0,1], A_{1}={\mathbb Q}\cap [0, 1], A_{2}=[0,1]\setminus A_{1}</m>, 
  then it is reasonable to argue that Dirichlet's non-Riemann integrable function on <m>[0,1]</m>
  could be regarded as integrable on both <m>A_{1}</m> and <m> A_{2}</m> as it is a 
  constant on either set, but its Riemann integral on <m>[0, 1]</m> is not defined. 
  One key issue is that Riemann's integration theory does not allow
   general sets such as <m> A_{2}</m> here 
   as cells in the partition, and each partition has to be a <em>finite</em>
  partition. As a result one can't directly define Riemann integral on a domain with infinite 
  length (area or volume) or when the integrand is unbounded.</p> </li>
  <li>A more serious issue is that <em>reasonable limits of Riemann integrable functions
  may not be Riemann integrable</em>. The rectification of this issue requires by Lebesgue's integration
  theory. </li>
  <li>The simplistic idea of using "nice cells" to partition a domain of integration becomes
  more challenging when one tries to carry it out to surfaces or hypersurfaces. The issue of 
  defining the area (volume) of cells on such surfaces has to be tackled first.</li>
  <li>A basic difficulty in discussing the integration on a surface is how to properly define a surface.
  Unlike in the case of a curve, which can always be thought of as defined through a map on
  an interval, there is no simple or canonical domain  which can be used to define a surface,
  except for a <em>patch</em> of a surface.</li>
  <li>For the purpose of integration theory on a surface, it suffices that one can partition
  the surface into some non-overlapping union of patches such that each patch has a 
 <em> parametric representation</em> through a map defined on a nice domain such as a
 rectangular box or simplex, and one defines the integration on each such patch on this nice domain
 through this parametrization. </li>
 <li>The implementation of the above approach still requires substantial preparation work.
 First, the existence and construction of such a partition would require careful proof. Second,
 there is usually no canonical parametrization for a patch of a surface, so one has to verify
 that different parametrizations do not lead to different values of the integrals.</li>

 </ol>
   </introduction>
   
   <section permid="section-int-def" xml:id="section-int-def">
   	<title>Basic definitions and properties for the integral of a scalar function on 
	a multi-dimensional rectangle </title>
	<p>There is little difference between one and higher dimensions in the discussion of
	this and next section; differences will show when discussing evaluation of integrals and change
	of variables.
	</p>
	<definition xml:id="hypercube">
		<idx>hypercube</idx><idx>partition</idx>
		<idx><h>hypercube</h><h><m>n</m>-dimensional rectangle</h><h>partition</h></idx>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\cP_{1}\times\cdots \times \cP_{n}</m></usage>
			<description>A partition of a hypercube defined in terms of a collection of
			partitions of its constitutive factors</description>
		</notation>
		<statement>
			<p>A set of the form <m>R=[a_{1}, b_{1}]\times \cdots \times [a_{n}, b_{n}]</m> ,
			 where <m>a_{i} &lt; b_{i}</m> for each <m>i</m>, is
			called a <term>hypercube</term> in <m>\bbR^{n}</m>. 
			We also informally call it an <m>n</m>-dimensional
			rectangle (or rectangular box). We define its <term>volume</term> to be
			<me>
			|R| := (b_{1}-a_{1})\cdots (b_{n}-a_{n}).
			</me>
			</p>
			<p> When <m>a_{i}=b_{i}</m> is allowed, and this equality holds for at least one <m>i</m>,
			we call such an <m>R</m> a degenerate hypercube (or informally a degenerate rectangle),
			and define its volume to be <m>0</m>.
			</p>
			<p>Suppose that <m>\cP_{i}</m> is a partition of <m>[a_{i}, b_{i}]</m> for <m>1\le i \le n</m>.
			Then these partitions <m>\cP_{i}</m>'s form a partition <m>\cP</m> of
			<m>R=[a_{1}, b_{1}]\times \cdots \times [a_{n}, b_{n}]</m> in the following sense:
			<ol label="(i).">
			<li> The cells of the partition <m>\cP</m> consist of  <m>
			\{S:=I_{1}\times\cdots \times I_{n}: I_{i} \text{ is a subinterval of  } \cP_{i}\}</m> ; 
			</li>
			<li>
			 The union of the cells of <m>\cP =I</m>;
			 </li>
			 <li>  The intersection of any two
			different cells of <m>\cP</m>  is either the empty set, or a degenerate rectangle; and 
			</li>
			<li> <m>\vert R\vert=\sum_{S\in \cP}\vert S\vert</m>.
			</li>
			</ol>
			We may denote this partition by <m>\cP_{1}\times\cdots \times \cP_{n}</m>.
			</p>
			<p>The <em>partition size</em> <m>\lambda(\cP)</m>
			of <m>\cP:=\cP_{1}\times\cdots \times \cP_{n}</m> is defined as
			<me>
			\lambda(\cP) :=\max\{\vert I_{i}\vert: S:=I_{1}\times\cdots\times I_{n} \in \cP\}.
			</me>
			</p>
			</statement>
			</definition>
			<remark>
				<p>Only the verification of the last property requires more than a few lines
				of argument. One easy way is to use an induction argument on <m>n</m>, the
				dimension. <m>R':=[a_{2}, b_{2}]\times \cdots \times [a_{n}, b_{n}]</m>
				is an <m>(n-1)</m>-dimensional rectangle, and the partitions 
				<m>\{\cP_{2},\ldots, \cP_{n}\}</m> form a partition <m>\cP'</m> of 
				<m>R'</m>. Suppose that <m>\{I_{1,1},\ldots, I_{1,k}\}</m> are the
				subintervals of <m>\cP_{1}</m>. In the summation
				<m>\sum_{S\in \cP}\vert S\vert</m>, group <m>S</m> according to its
				constitutive factor in the first variable: each <m>S</m> has the form
				of <m>I_{1,j}\times S'</m> for some <m>I_{1,j}\in \cP_{1}</m> 
				and <m>S'\in \cP'</m>, thus we have
				<me>
				\sum_{S\in \cP}\vert S\vert=\sum_{I_{1,j}\in \cP_{1}}\sum_{S'\in \cP'}
				\vert I_{1,j} \times S'\vert.
				</me>
				By induction, we have 
				<me>\sum_{S'\in \cP'}
				\vert I_{1,j} \times S'\vert= \vert I_{1,j}\vert \sum_{S'\in \cP'}
				\vert  S'\vert= \vert I_{1,j}\vert \vert R'\vert.
				</me>
				It now follows that
				<me>
				\sum_{S\in \cP}\vert S\vert=\sum_{I_{1,j}\in \cP_{1}} \vert I_{1,j}\vert \vert R'\vert
				=(b_{1}-a_{1})  \vert R'\vert=\vert R\vert.
				</me>
				  </p>
				  <p>Note that a partition of <m>R</m> in our definition is defined in terms of 
				  a collection of partitions <m>\cP_{i}</m> for each constitutive factor. As a result,
				  if the projection onto a factor
				   of two rectangles <m>S_{1}, S_{2}</m> in  a partition of <m>R</m> share more than
				   one points, they must have identical subinterval in that factor. One could allow more
				   general choices of rectangles in a partition; it would just make it harder to bookkeep 
				   such rectangles, and our definition suffices for our purpose of defining the integral of a
				   function.
				   </p>
			</remark>
			<definition xml:id="def-integral-scalar">
				<idx>integral of a scalar function</idx><idx>Riemann sum</idx>
				<idx>upper sum</idx><idx>lower sum</idx>
				<notation>
					<usage><m>\int_{R}\, f</m>, <m>\int_{R}\, f\, d\bx</m></usage>
					<description>The definition of the Riemann sum, upper sum, lower sum,
					and  integral of a scalar function on
					a hypercube <m>R</m></description>
				</notation>
				<statement>
				<p>Suppose that <m>f</m> is a bounded real-valued function defined on the rectangle 
				<m>R</m>, <m>\cP</m> a partition of <m>R</m>, and a point
				<m>\bx_{\alpha}\in R_{\alpha}</m> is chosen for each sub rectangle 
				<m>R_{\alpha}</m> of <m>\cP</m>. We define the corresponding	
				<term>Riemann sum</term> as
				<me>
				R(f, \cP, \{\bx_{\alpha}\}):=\sum_{\alpha} f(\bx_{\alpha}) \vert R_{\alpha} \vert.
				</me>
				</p>
				<p>Define
				<me>M_{S}(f):=\sup_{\bx\in S}f(\bx) \quad \text{and} \quad 
				m_{S}(f):=\inf_{\bx\in S}f(\bx) 
				</me>
				as the supremum, and respectively infimum, of <m>f</m> on the rectangle <m>S</m>.
				Then the <term>upper sum</term> <m>U(f, \cP)</m>, and respectively the 
				<term>lower sum</term> <m>L(f, \cP)</m>, 
				of <m>f</m> on <m>R</m> with respect to the partition <m>\cP</m>
				is defined as
				<me>
				U(f, \cP) :=\sum_{\alpha} M_{S_{\alpha}}(f) \vert S_{\alpha}\vert,
				\quad
				L(f, \cP) :=\sum_{\alpha} m_{S_{\alpha}}(f) \vert S_{\alpha}\vert.
				</me>
				</p>
				</statement>
				</definition>
				<p>Note that 
				<me>
				L(f, \cP)\le R(f, \cP, \{\bx_{\alpha}\})\le U(f, \cP).
				</me>
				We are interested in whether <m>R(f, \cP, \{\bx_{\alpha}\})</m> has a limit
				as <m>\lambda (\cP)\to 0</m> which is independent of how
				<m>\bx_{\alpha}\in S_{\alpha}</m> is chosen. It is easier to study
				whether <m>U(f, \cP)</m>, and respectively <m>L(f, \cP)</m>, has a limit
				as <m>\lambda (\cP)\to 0</m>.
				</p>
				<definition xml:id="def-refinement-partition">
					<idx>refinement of a partition</idx>
					<statement>
					A partition <m>\cP^{*}:=\cP^{*}_{1}\times\cdots \times \cP^{*}_{n}</m>
					is called a <term>refinement</term>
					 of partition <m>\cP:=\cP_{1}\times\cdots \times \cP_{n}</m>
					if each <m>\cP^{*}_{i}</m> is a refinement of <m>\cP_{i}</m>.
					</statement>
					</definition>
					<figure xml:id="fig-partition-refinement">
						<caption>An illustration of a common refinement of two given partitions</caption>
						<image width="50%"  height="50%" source="•">
							<description>•</description>
						</image>
					</figure>
					<p>Note that if <m>\cP^{*}</m> is a refinement of partition <m>\cP</m>, then
					<m>\lambda(\cP^{*})\le \lambda(\cP)</m>, and that
					<me>
					U(f, \cP^{*})\le U(f, \cP), L(f, \cP^{*})\ge L(f, \cP).
					</me>
					 Just as in one dimension, if
					<m>\cP_{1}, \cP_{2}</m> are two partitions of <m>R</m>,
					then there is a partition <m>\cP^{*}</m> which is a refinement of both 
					<m>\cP_{1}</m> and <m> \cP_{2}</m>, and there is an essentially
					canonical way of constructing such an <m>\cP^{*}</m> by adjoining all
					the end points of the subintervals of the factors of <m>\cP_{1}, \cP_{2}</m>.
					</p>
					<definition xml:id="def-upperlower-int-def">
						<idx>upper integral, lower integral</idx>
						<notation>
							<usage><m>\upint_{R}\,f, \lowint_{R}\,f </m></usage>
							<description>upper integral and lower integral of a function on a set</description>
						</notation>
						<statement>
						Suppose that <m>f</m> is a bounded function defined
					on the rectangle <m>R\subset \bbR^{n}</m>. Then its upper integral,
					and respectively lower integral, on
					<m> R</m> is defined as <m>\inf_{\cP}U(f, \cP)</m>, 
					and respectively <m>\sup_{\cP}U(f, \cP)</m>, where
					<m>\cP</m> runs over all partitions of <m>\cP</m>. 
					The upper integral is denoted
					as <m>\upint_{R}\,f</m>, while the lower integral is denoted
					as <m>\lowint_{R}\,f</m>.
					</statement>
					</definition>
							
					<proposition xml:id="propos-upperlower-int">
					<title>Basic property of upper and lower integral of 
					a bounded real-valued function defined
					on a rectangle</title>
					<statement>Suppose that <m>f</m> is a bounded function defined
					on the rectangle <m>R\subset \bbR^{n}</m>. Then
					<me>
					 \upint_{R}\,f= \lim_{\lambda(\cP)\to 0} U(f, \cP),
					</me>
					and
					<me>
					 \lowint_{R}\,f = \lim_{\lambda(\cP)\to 0} L(f, \cP).
					</me>
					Furthermore,
					<me>
					 \lowint_{R}\,f \le  \upint_{R}\,f.
					</me>
					<proof> <p> Let <m>\cP_{1}, \cP_{2}</m> be two arbitrary partitions of <m>R</m>,
					and <m>\cP^{*}</m> be a refinement of both 
					<m>\cP_{1}</m> and <m> \cP_{2}</m>. Then
					<me>
					L(f, \cP_{1})\le L(f, \cP^{*})\le U(f, \cP^{*})\le U(f, \cP_{2}).
					</me>
					As a result,   
										<me>
		L(f, \cP_{1})\le  \upint_{R} \, f =\inf_{\cP_{2}} U(f, \cP_{2}),
		</me>
		and 
		<me>
		\lowint_{R} \, f =\sup_{\cP_{1}} L(f, \cP_{1})\le \upint_{R} \, f.
		</me>
		</p>
		<p>
		For any <m>\epsilon>0</m>, first find a partition <m>\cP_{2}</m> of <m>R</m> such that
		<me>
		\upint_{R} \, f \le U(f, \cP_{2}) \le \upint_{R} \, f + \epsilon.
		</me>
		Now take any partition <m>\cP</m> of <m>R</m> of small partition size <m>\lambda(\cP)</m>
		(to be determined). Let <m>\cP^{*}</m> be the canonical refinement of
		 <m>\cP</m> and <m>\cP_{2}</m>. Then
		 <me>
		\upint_{R} \, f \le U(f, \cP_{*}) \le U(f, \cP_{2}) \le \upint_{R} \, f + \epsilon.
		</me>
		and there exists a number <m>N</m> depending only
		 on the  partition <m>\cP_{2}</m> such that in the sums 
		 <m>U(f,\cP)</m> and <m>U(f, \cP^{*})</m>, all but at most <m>N</m> terms may differ,
		 as in the construction of <m>\cP^{*}</m>, the number of sub intervals of the factors
		 of <m>\cP</m> that need to be refined in relation to <m>\cP_{2}</m> has a bound that depends 
		 only on <m>\cP_{2}</m>. 
		 Note that  each term that may differ has a factor from the volume of
		 the sub rectangle which is bounded above by <m>(\lambda(\cP))^{n}</m>,
		 and  the remaining factor is bounded above in absolute value by <m>\sup_{R}|f|</m>, thus 
		 each such term  is bounded above in absolute value by
		 <m>\sup_{R}|f| (\lambda(\cP))^{n}</m>, as a result
		 <me>
		 \vert U(f,\cP)- U(f, \cP^{*})\vert \le N \sup_{R}|f| (\lambda(\cP))^{n}.
		 </me>
		 It now follows that there exists some <m>\delta >0</m> such that whenever
		 <m>\lambda(\cP) &lt; \delta</m> we have
		 <me>
		 \vert U(f,\cP)- U(f, \cP^{*})\vert &lt; \epsilon  \text{ so }  U(f,\cP) &lt; \upint_{R} \, f + 2\epsilon,
		 </me>
		 proving that <m>\lim_{\lambda(\cP)\to 0} U(f, \cP)= \upint_{R} \, f</m>.
		 </p>
		<p>
		The proof of <m>\sup_{\cP}L(f, \cP) = \lim_{\lambda(\cP)\to 0} L(f, \cP)</m> is done in a similar way.
		</p>
		</proof>
					</statement>
					</proposition>
		<definition xml:id="def-riemann-integrable">
			<idx>Riemann integrable function</idx>
			<notation>
				<usage><m>\int_{R}\, f</m></usage>
				<description>The Riemann integral of <m>f</m></description>
			</notation>
						<statement><p>A bounded real-valued function <m>f</m> defined 
						on a rectangle <m>R</m> is called <term>Riemann integrable</term>,
						if there exists a real number <m>S</m> such that
						<m>\lim_{\lambda(P)\to 0} R(f, \cP, \{\bx_{\alpha}\})=S</m>
						in the sense that for any <m>\epsilon >0</m>, there exists some
						<m>\delta >0</m> that
						<me>
						\vert R(f, \cP, \{\bx_{\alpha}\}) -S\vert &lt; \epsilon
						</me>
						for any partition <m>\cP</m> and choice of
						<m>\bx_{\alpha}\in R_{\alpha}\in \cP</m>,
						as long as <m>\lambda(P) &lt; \delta</m>.
						</p>
						<p>When such an <m>S</m> exists, it is unique, and we denote
						it by <m>\int_{R}\, f</m>.
						</p>
						</statement>
						</definition>
						<theorem xml:id="thm-int-linear">
							<title>Linearity of integral</title>
							<statement>
								<p>Suppose that <m>f_{1}, f_{2}</m> are Riemann 
								integrable on <m>R</m>, and <m>c_{1}, c_{2}</m> are 
								constants, then <m>c_{1}f_{1}+c_{2}f_{2}</m> is also
								Riemann 
								integrable on <m>R</m>, and 
								<men xml:id="eqn-int-linearity">
								\int_{R}\left( c_{1}f_{1}+c_{2}f_{2}\right) 
								= c_{1} \int_{R} f_{1} + c_{2} \int_{R} f_{2}.
								</men>
								</p>
							</statement>
							<proof>
								<p>Let <m>S_{1}= \int_{R} f_{1}</m> and
								<m>S_{2}= \int_{R} f_{2}</m>. Then for any <m>\epsilon >0</m>,
								there exists <m>\delta>0</m> such that for any 
								partition <m>\cP</m> of <m>R</m>, whenever 
								<m>\lambda (\cP) &lt; \delta</m>, we have
								<md>
							<mrow> \vert R(f_{1}, \cP, \{\bx_{\alpha}\}) -S_{1}\vert &lt; \epsilon,</mrow>
							<mrow> \vert R(f_{2}, \cP, \{\bx_{\alpha}\}) -S_{2}\vert &lt; \epsilon.</mrow>
								</md>
								Then
								<me>
								\vert R(c_{1}f_{1}+c_{2}f_{2}, \cP, \{\bx_{\alpha}\}) -
								\left(c_{1}S_{1}+c_{2 S_{2 \right)}}\vert
								\le |c_{1}| \vert R(f_{1}, \cP, \{\bx_{\alpha}\}) -S_{1}\vert
								+ |c_{2}| \vert R(f_{2}, \cP, \{\bx_{\alpha}\}) -S_{2}\vert
								\vert &lt; \left(|c_{1}|+|c_{2}| \right) \epsilon,
								</me>
								which shows the integrability of <m>c_{1}f_{1}+c_{2}f_{2}</m>
								as well as <xref ref="eqn-int-linearity"/>.
								 </p>
							</proof>
						</theorem>
						<p> Based on  Proposition <xref ref="propos-upperlower-int"/>, 
						a <em>necessary condition</em>
						that <m>f </m> be Riemann integrable on <m>R</m> is that
						<men xml:id="eqn-Darboux" label="eqn-Darboux">
						\lowint_{R} \, f  =\upint_{R}\, f.
						</men>
						This turns out to be also <em>sufficient</em>.
						</p>
						<theorem>
							<title>Riemann integrability criterion</title>
							<statement>A bounded real-valued function <m>f</m> defined on the
						rectangle <m>R</m> is Riemann integrable iff 
						 <xref ref="eqn-Darboux"/> holds.
							</statement>
							<proof> We only need to prove the if part. Suppose 
							 <xref ref="eqn-Darboux"/> holds. 
			Call the value on both sides <m>\int_{R}\, f</m>. 
			Our proof in  Proposition <xref ref="propos-upperlower-int"/>essentially
							carries over to show that, for any <m>\epsilon >0</m>, there 
							exists some <m>\delta >0</m>, such that for any partition
							<m>\cP</m> of <m>R</m> with <m>\lambda(\cP) &lt; \delta</m>, we 
							have
							<me>
						\int_{R}\, f-\epsilon &lt; L(f, \cP) \le \int_{R}\, f \le U(f, \cP) &lt; \int_{R}\, f +\epsilon.
							</me>
							Then for any choice of <m>\bx_{\alpha}\in R_{\alpha}\in \cP</m>, we 
							have
							<me>
						\int_{R}\, f-\epsilon &lt; L(f, \cP) \le R(f, \cP, \{\bx_{\alpha}\})\le U(f, \cP) &lt; \int_{R}\, f +\epsilon,
							</me>
							which shows that <m>f</m> is Riemann integrable on <m>R</m>.
							</proof>
							
						
						</theorem>
						<example> <p> Let
						<me>f(x)=\begin{cases} 1 \quad x \in [0, 1] \text{ rational, } \\
									0 \quad x \in [0, 1] \text{ irrational; } 
									\end{cases}
									</me>
			<me>g(x, y) =\begin{cases} 1 \quad x \in [0, 1] \text{ rational,}  y=0\\
								0 \quad \text{ elsewhere in } [0, 1]\times[0, 1]; 
								\end{cases}
								</me>
								and <m>h(x, y)=f(x)f(y)</m>.
									</p>
								<p> <m>f</m> is discontinuous everywhere on <m>[0,1]</m>,
								<m>g</m> is continuous on <m>[0,1]\times (0, 1]</m>,
								but is discontinuous on <m>[0, 1]\times \{0\}</m>,
							while <m>h</m> is discontinuous everywhere on <m>[0,1]\times[0,1]</m>.
							</p>
<p>For any partition <m>\cP_{1}: 0=s_{0} &lt;  s_{1} &lt; \cdots &lt; s_{k}=1 </m> of <m>[0, 1]</m> in the
<m>x</m> variable,  <m>U(f, \cP_{1})=1</m> and <m>L(f, \cP_{1})=0</m>. Thus
<m>\lowint_{[0,1]}\, f(x)\, dx =0</m> , <m>\upint_{[0, 1]}\, f(x)\, dx =1</m>, and <m>f</m> is not
integrable on <m>[0, 1]</m>.
</p>
<p>For any partition <m>\cP_{2}: 0=t_{0} &lt;  t_{1} &lt; \cdots &lt; t_{l}=1 </m> of <m>[0, 1]</m> in the
<m>y</m> variable,  <m>m(g, [s_{i-1},s_{i}]\times[t_{j-1}, t_{j} ])=0</m> for all <m>i, j</m>, and 
<me>
M(g, [s_{i-1},s_{i}]\times[t_{j-1}, t_{j} ])=\begin{cases} 1 \quad j=0,\\
0 \quad j>1. 
\end{cases}
</me>
Thus <m>L(g, \cP_{1}\times \cP_{2})=0</m>, <m>U(g, \cP_{1}\times \cP_{2})=t_{1}</m>,
and <m>\lowint_{[0,1]\times [0,1]}\, g =0</m>,   <m> \upint_{[0,1]\times [0,1]}\, g =0</m>, so
we conclude that <m>g</m> is Riemann integrable on <m>[0,1]\times [0,1]</m>,
and <m>\int_{[0,1]\times [0,1]} g =0</m>.  
</p>
<p>For <m>h</m>, we have <m>m(h, [s_{i-1},s_{i}]\times[t_{j-1}, t_{j} ])=0,
m(h, [s_{i-1},s_{i}]\times[t_{j-1}, t_{j} ])=1</m> for all <m>i, j</m>, so <m>L(h, \cP_{1}\times \cP_{2})=0</m>, <m>U(g, \cP_{1}\times \cP_{2})=1</m>. As a result, <m>\lowint_{[0,1]\times [0,1]}\, h =0</m>,
<m>\upint_{[0,1]\times [0,1]}\, h =1</m>, so <m>h</m> is not Riemann integrable on <m>[0,1]\times [0,1]</m>.
</p>
						</example>
						</section>
						<section xml:id="section-int-criterioa"><title>Further Riemann
						integrability criteria</title>
						<p>
			To find a more easily checkable criterion for 	<xref ref="eqn-Darboux"/> , we 
			first make the following definition.</p>
			<definition xml:id="def-osc">
				<idx>oscillation of a function</idx>
				<notation>
					<usage><m>\osc(f, R)</m> and <m>\osc(f)(\bx)</m></usage>
					<description>
					The oscillation of a function <m>f</m> over a set <m>S</m>.
					 The oscillation of a function <m>f</m>  at a point <m>\bx</m>. </description>
				</notation>
				<statement>
				<p> 
				Let <m>f</m> be defined on <m>R</m>. 
				The oscillation of a function <m>f</m> over the set <m>S \subset R</m> is defined to be
				<me>
				\sup_{S}f - \inf_{S}f = M(f, S)-m(f, S)
				</me>
				and is denoted as <m>\osc(f, S)</m>. 
				</p>
				<p>
				The oscillation of a function <m>f</m>  at a point <m>\bx</m> 
				is defined to be
				<me>
				\lim_{r\searrow 0} \osc(f, R\cap B(\bx, r)),
				</me>
				and is denoted as <m>\osc(f)(\bx)</m>. Here <m>B(\bx, r)</m> is the open ball of radius 
				<m>r</m> centered at <m>\bx</m>.
				</p>
				</statement>
				</definition>
				<p>Note that we could replace the open ball <m>B(\bx, r)</m> by its closure in
				<m>R\cap B(\bx, r)</m> in the definition of <m>\osc(f)(\bx)</m>. Furthermore,
				<me>\lim_{r\searrow 0} \osc(f, R\cap B(\bx, r))=\lim_{s\searrow 0} \osc(f, R\cap R(\bx, s))
				=\lim_{s\searrow 0} \osc(f, R\cap \bar{R}(\bx, s))</me>,
				where <m>R(\bx, s)</m> denotes the open rectangle centered at <m>\bx</m> with
				<m>2s</m> as its side length.  This follows from the relation
				<me>
				\osc(f, U) \le \osc(f, V) \text{ whenever } U\subset V,
				</me>
				and <m>B(\bx, r) \subset R(\bx, r) \subset B(\bx, \sqrt{n}r)</m>.
				</p>
				<p>Note also that <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>\bx</m> iff <m>\osc(f)(\bx)=0</m>.
				</p>
				<exercise><p>Suppose that <m>\bx \in U \subset R</m>. Is it true that
				<m>\osc(f)(\bx)\le \osc(f, U)</m>?</p>
				</exercise>
				<proposition><title>Upper semi-continuity of <m>\osc(f)(\bx)</m></title>
				<statement>The function <m>	\osc(f)(\bx)</m> is upper 	semi-continuous. As a consequence, for any real number <m>a</m>, the set <m>\{\bx: 	\osc(f)(\bx)\ge a \}</m> is closed.
				</statement>
				<proof>
				<p> For any real number <m>a</m>, if <m>\bx_{0}\in \{\bx: 	\osc(f)(\bx) &lt; a\}</m>,
				then there exists some <m>r>0</m> such that
				<m> \osc(f, B(\bx_{0}, r)) &lt; a</m>. For any <m>\bx \in B(\bx_{0}, r)</m>,
				we observe that <m>\osc(f)(\bx)\le \osc(f, B(\bx_{0}, r)) &lt; a</m>. Thus
				<m>B(\bx_{0}, r) \subset \{\bx: 	\osc(f)(\bx) &lt; a\}</m>, proving that the latter is open.
				</p>
				</proof>
				</proposition>		
				<p> Note that 
				<men xml:id="eqn-discont">\{\bx: f \text{ discontinuous at } \bx\}=
				\cup_{k\in \bbN} \{\by: \osc(f)(\by)\ge \frac 1k\},
				</men>
				namely, <m>\{\bx: f \text{ discontinuous at } \bx\}</m> is a countable union of
				of the closed sets <m>\{\by: \osc(f)(\by)\ge \frac 1k\}</m>.
				 </p>
				<theorem xml:id="thm-Riemann-integrability-oscillation">
					<title>Riemann integrability criterion in terms of the oscillation of the integrand</title>
					<statement>
						<p>A bounded real-valued function <m>f</m> defined on the
						rectangle <m>R</m> is Riemann integrable iff 
						<men xml:id="eqn-int-osc" label="eqn-int-osc">
						\forall \epsilon >0, \exists  \text{ a partition }
						\cP:=\{R_{\alpha}\} \text{ such that } 
						\sum_{\alpha} \osc(f,R_{\alpha})\vert R_{\alpha} \vert &lt; \epsilon.
						</men> </p>
						<p>
						In particular, if <m>f</m> is continuous on the closed rectangle
						<m>R</m>, then <m>f</m> is Riemann integrable on <m>R</m>.</p>
					</statement>
					<proof>
						<p>Suppose that <m>f</m> is Riemann integrable on <m>R</m> and that
						<m>\epsilon>0</m> is given. Our proof of  Proposition <xref ref="propos-upperlower-int"/>gives
						us a partition <m>\cP:=\{R_{\alpha}\}</m> such that
						<me>
						\int_{R}\, f -\frac{\epsilon}{2} &lt; L(f, \cP)\le \int_{R}\, f \le 
						U (f, \cP)  &lt; \int_{R}\, f  + \frac{\epsilon}{2},
						</me>
						which implies that
						<me>
						\sum_{\alpha} \osc(f,R_{\alpha})\vert R_{\alpha} \vert
						=U (f, \cP)-L (f, \cP) &lt; \epsilon.
						</me>
						</p>
						<p>Suppose that <xref ref="eqn-int-osc"/> holds. 
						Then <m>U (f, \cP)-L (f, \cP) &lt; \epsilon,</m>  and
						<me>
						0\le \upint_{R}\, f  -\lowint_{R} \, f  \le U (f, \cP)-L (f, \cP) &lt; \epsilon.
						</me>
						Since <m>\epsilon >0</m> is arbitrary, it follows that
						<m> \upint_{R}\, f -\lowint_{R} \, f=0</m>,  and  
						<m>f</m> is Riemann integrable on <m>R</m>.
						</p>
						<p>Finally, suppose that <m>f</m> is continuous on the closed rectangle
						<m>R</m>, then it is uniformly continuous on 
						<m>R</m>. For any given <m>\epsilon >0</m>, there exists
						<m>\delta >0</m> such that for any partition <m>\cP:=\{R_{\alpha}\}</m>
						of <m>R</m> with <m>\lambda (P) &lt; \delta</m>, we have
						<m>\osc(f, R_{\alpha}) &lt; \epsilon/\vert R\vert</m> for all 
						<m>R_{\alpha} \in \cP</m>. It then follows that
						<me>
						\sum_{\alpha} \osc(f,R_{\alpha})\vert R_{\alpha} \vert \le \epsilon,
						</me>
						proving the Riemann integrability of <m>f</m> on <m>R</m>.
						</p>
					</proof>
				</theorem>
				<p> Note that when <m>f</m> is continuous on the closed rectangle <m>R</m>,
				we achieve <xref ref="eqn-int-osc"/> by constructing a partition 
				<m>\cP:=\{R_{\alpha}\}</m>
				of <m>R</m> such that <m>\osc(f, R_{\alpha}) &lt; \epsilon/\vert R\vert</m> for all 
						<m>R_{\alpha} \in \cP</m>. We can also achieve
						<xref ref="eqn-int-osc"/> if we can construct a partition
						<m>\cP:=\{R_{\alpha}\}</m>
				of <m>R</m> such that the sum of volume of those rectangles <m>R_{\alpha}</m>,
				for which <m>\osc(f, R_{\alpha})\ge \epsilon/(2\vert R\vert)</m>, can be made smaller
				than <m>\epsilon/(2\osc(f, R))</m> ,
				as the factors <m>(f, R_{\alpha})</m> have a uniform upper bound <m>\osc(f, R)</m>
				for a given bounded function <m>f</m> on <m>R</m>.
				We will exploit some properties of <m>\osc(f)(\bx)</m> for this.
				</p>
				
			<definition xml:id="def-content0-measure0">
				<idx>Set of content <m>0</m>, set of measure <m>0</m></idx>
								<statement>
								<p> A set <m>S\subset \bbR^{n}</m> is said to have 
								content <m>0</m>, if for any <m>\epsilon >0</m>, there exists
								a <em>finite</em> cover <m>\{R_{i}\} </m> 
								of <m>S</m> by rectangles such that
								<me>
								\sum_{i}\vert R_{i}\vert &lt; \epsilon.
								</me>
								</p>
								<p>A set <m>S\subset \bbR^{n}</m> is said to have 
								measure <m>0</m>, if for any <m>\epsilon >0</m>, there exists
								an <em>at most countable</em> cover <m>\{R_{i}\} </m> 
								of <m>S</m> by rectangles such that
								<me>
								\sum_{i}\vert R_{i}\vert &lt; \epsilon.
								</me>
								</p>
								</statement>
								</definition>
								<proposition><title>Relation between sets of content <m>0</m>
								and sets of measure <m>0</m></title>
								<ol>
		<li> A set of content <m>0</m> must be a set of measure <m>0</m>.</li>
		<li>The closure of a set of content <m>0</m> must be a set of  content <m>0</m>.</li>
		<li> A countable union of sets of content <m>0</m> must be a set of measure <m>0</m>.
As a consequence, a countable union of sets of content <m>0</m> must be a set of measure <m>0</m>.</li>
		<li>A <em>compact</em> set of measure <m>0</m> is also a set of content <m>0</m>.</li>
		</ol>
		<proof>
		<p>The first and second properties are obvious. For the third one, suppose
		<m>S=\cup_{i}S_{i}</m>, where each <m>S_{i}</m> is a set of measure <m>0</m>.
		For any <m>\epsilon>0</m>, there exists an at most countable  cover 
		<m>\{R_{i\,j}\}_{j=1}^{N_{i}}</m> (<m>N_{i}</m> could be <m>\infty</m>)
		of <m>S_{i}</m> such that <m>\sum_{j=1}^{N_{i}}\vert R_{i\,j}\vert &lt; \frac{\epsilon}{2^{i}}</m>.
		Then <m>\{R_{i\,j}: i\in \bbN, 1\le j \le N_{i}\}</m> is an at most countable cover of
		<m>S</m>, and
		<me>
		\sum_{i}\sum_{j=1}^{N_{i}}\vert R_{i\,j}\vert &lt; \sum_{i} \frac{\epsilon}{2^{i}}=\epsilon,
		</me>
		proving that <m>S</m> is a set of measure <m>0</m>.
		</p>
		<p>For the last property, suppose <m>S</m> is a compact set of measure <m>0</m>.
		For <m>\epsilon>0</m> we can choose a cover of <m>S</m> by  <em>open</em>
		rectangles <m>\{R_{i}\} </m> such that 
		<m>\sum_{i}\vert R_{i}\vert &lt; \epsilon</m>. Using the compactness of <m>S</m>, we can
		then select a finite sub cover which satisfies the desired property.
		</p>
		
		</proof>
		</proposition>
					<p>The set <m>\bbQ</m> of rationals in <m>\bbR</m> is a set of
					measure <m>0</m>, but not a set of content <m>0</m>; its closure,
					<m>\bbR</m>, is not a set of measure <m>0</m>.
					</p>		
					<p>We are now ready to formulate the following theorem.</p>
					<theorem xml:id="thm-integrability-osc0">
						<title>Riemann integrability in terms of set of discontinuity</title>
						<statement>
							<p>A bounded function <m>f</m> on a bounded closed rectangle
							<m>R</m> is Riemann integrable on <m>R</m> iff its set
							of discontinuity has measure <m>0</m>.</p>
						</statement>
						<proof>
							<p>We will use <xref ref="eqn-discont"/>.
							</p>
							<p>Suppose that <m>f</m> is Riemann integrable on <m>R</m>.
							For each <m>k\in \bbN</m>, we will prove that
							<m>D_{k}:=\{\by: \osc(f)(\by)\ge \frac 1k\}</m> is a set of
							content <m>0</m>. </p>
							<p>Given any <m>\epsilon >0</m>. There exists a partition
							<m>\cP=\{R_{\alpha}\}</m> of <m>R</m> such that
							<me>
							\sum_{\alpha} \osc(f, R_{\alpha})\vert R_{\alpha} \vert &lt; \frac{\epsilon}{2k}.
							</me>
							The rectangles in <m>\cP</m> are divided into two
							subgroups: the subgroup <m>\cL_{k}</m> consisting
							those <m>R_{\alpha}</m> such that
							<m>\osc(f, R_{\alpha})\ge \frac{1}{2k}</m>, and 
							the subgroup <m>\cS_{k}</m> consisting
							those <m>R_{\alpha}</m> such that
							<m>\osc(f, R_{\alpha})&lt; \frac{1}{2k}</m>. Then
							it follows from
							<me>
							\frac{1}{2k} \sum_{R_{\alpha}\in \cL_{k} } \vert R_{\alpha} \vert \le
				\sum_{R_{\alpha}\in \cL_{k} } \osc(f, R_{\alpha})\vert R_{\alpha} \vert &lt; \frac{\epsilon}{2k}
							</me>
							that
							<me>
							\sum_{R_{\alpha}\in \cL_{k} } \vert R_{\alpha} \vert &lt; \epsilon.
							</me>
							</p>
							<p>
							We now claim that 
							<me>D_{k}\subset \cup_{R_{\alpha}\in \cL_{k} } R_{\alpha}.
							</me>
							This will show that <m>D_{k}</m> is a set of content <m>0</m>.
							</p>
							<p>
							If the claim were not true, there would exist some <m>\bx \in D_{k}
							\setminus \cup_{R_{\alpha}\in \cL_{k} } R_{\alpha}</m>.  
							Thus <m>\bx \in \cup_{R_{\alpha}\in \cS_{k} } R_{\alpha}</m>.
							Since the complement of <m>\cup_{R_{\alpha}\in \cL_{k} } R_{\alpha}</m>
							is open, there exists some ball <m>B(\bx, r)
							\subset \cup_{R_{\alpha}\in \cS_{k} } R_{\alpha}</m>.
							If <m>\bx\in \text{ interior}(R_{\alpha})</m> for some
							<m>R_{\alpha} \in \cS_{k}</m>, it would force
							<m>\frac 1k \le \osc(f)(\bx)\le \osc(f, R_{\alpha}) &lt; \frac{1}{2k}</m>,
							which would be a contradiction. So <m>\bx</m> can only be
							on the boundary of one or more <m>R_{\alpha} \in \cS_{k}</m>.
							We can choose <m>r>0</m> small enough such that
							any <m>\by\in B(\bx, r)</m> and <m>\bx</m> will be in one such
							common rectangle. Therefore, 
							<m>\vert f(\by)-f(\bx)\vert &lt; \frac{1}{2k}</m>. This would lead to
							<m>\osc(f)(\bx)\le \osc(f, B(\bx, r)) &lt; \frac 1k</m>,
							contradicting <m>\bx \in D_{k}</m>.
							</p>
							<p>The proof for the if part will be added.</p>
						</proof>
					</theorem>
   </section>
</chapter>
